{"title_page": "Ahmad Almutairi", "text_new": "{{short description|Kuwaiti para-sport athlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    =\n| name           = Ahmad Almutairi\n| image          = \n| image_size     = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels.-->\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     =\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = Kuwaiti \n| residence      = Kuwait City\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|05|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| weight         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| website        =\n| country        = Great Britain\n| sport          = [[Track and field]]<br/>[[Wheelchair basketball]]\n|disability_class= [[T33 (classification)|T33]] (athletics)\n| event          = sprint, javelin\n| club           = Kuwait Para-Sports Club\n| team           =\n| turnedpro      =\n| coach          = Mohamed Farhan\n| worlds         =\n| regionals      =\n| nationals      =\n| olympics       =\n| paralympics    = [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]\n| highestranking =\n| pb             =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport |Athletics}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{KUW}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Summer Paralympics]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 Paralympic Games|2016 Rio]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres T33|100m \u2013 T33]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m \u2013 T33]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T33]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Asian Para Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 Asian Para Games|2014 Incheon]] | 100m - T34}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 Asian Para Games|2014 Incheon]] | 200m - T34}}\n| show-medals    =\n| updated        =\n}}\n\n'''Ahmad Almutairi''' (born 13 May 1994) is a [[Kuwait]]i para-sport athlete who competes as a [[T33 (classification)|T33 classification]] [[track and field]] athlete and as a [[wheelchair basketball]] player, both at national level.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=903822&refreshauto=1|title=Almutairi, Ahmed|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> Despite the fact that Almutairi held the Paralympic world record for his classification in the 100m, 200m, 400m and 800m events, major world titles alluded him due to the fact that his classification was under-represented and he was forced to compete against less severely disabled athletes in the [[T44 (classification)|T44 class]]. He eventually won a gold medal at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]].\n\n==Personal history==\nAlmutairi was born in Kuwait in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_QA2015AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=10427.htm|title=Athlete profile: Ahmed Almutairi|work=Paralympics.org|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> At birth he was diagnosed with [[cerebral palsy]], which has resulted in Almutairi having very limited movement below the waist.<ref name=\"Al-Naqeeb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arabtimesonline.com/news/for-disabled-sky-is-the-limit-al-mutairi-paralympics-gold-medalist-inspires-kuwaiti-youths-with-disabilities/|title=For disabled, sky is the limit: Al-Mutairi \u2013 Paralympics gold medalist inspires Kuwaiti youths with disabilities|date=7 December 2015|work=Arab Times Online|accessdate=1 August 2016|first=Ahmed |last=Al-Naqeeb}}</ref> Due to his cerebral palsy, Almutairi was educated at a school for special needs children.<ref name=\"Al-Naqeeb\"/>\n\n==Athletics career==\nAmutairi was introduced to sport while at school, playing [[wheelchair basketball]]. One of his PE teachers saw potential in Amutairi and suggested that he join the Kuwaiti Sports Club for the Disabled.<ref name=\"Al-Naqeeb\"/> Initially he joined the basketball team, but after five months one of the trainers advised him to diversify into other sports to reach his full potential.<ref name=\"Al-Naqeeb\"/> Amutairi tried out [[wheelchair racing]] and found that he excelled at the sport.<ref name=\"Al-Naqeeb\"/> He became classified as a [[T33 (classification)|T33 classification]] athlete and in 2009 he entered his first track and field competition, held in the [[United Arab Emirates]]. Amutairi's results at the meet saw him qualify for the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Christchurch. At the World Championship Amutairi entered four events, the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m]], [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m]], [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metres|400m]] and the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's javelin throw|javelin throw]]. All three sprint events were for T34 athletes, with no T33 competitions available. Despite setting a championship record in all three races, Almutairi failed to finish on the podium, being beaten in each event by the less disadvantaged T34 competitors.<ref name=\"Al-Naqeeb\"/> This situation repeated itself throughout Almutairi's early career, and it was not until 2015 that he was able to compete on a level playing field at a major international event.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n[[File:Kuwait Paralympic team at the London 2012 Opening Ceremony.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Almutairi, first wheelchair behind the flag bearer, at the opening ceremony of the 2012 Paralympics.]]\nIn 2012 Almutairi was selected for the Kuwait team at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Summer Paralympics in London]]. In the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres T34|100m (T34)]] he set a new T33 world record of 17.67, but this was not good enough to see him through the heats. This same situation occurred in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres T34|200m]], where he set another world record (31.02), but failed to finish fast enough to reach the finals. He also competed in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's javelin throw|T33/34 javelin]], but his only legal throw of 17.34 saw him drop out in the first round.\n\nThe next year Almutairi travelled to Lyon to compete in the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]]. He was again forced to compete in the T34 events and failed to get out of the heats in the 100m, 200m and 400m races. His first major medal success came the following year at the [[2014 Asian Para Games]] in [[Incheon]] where, with a weaker field than in the Paralympics or the World Championships, he was able to win two silver medals in the 100m and 200m T34 races.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> Throughout 2015 Almutairi continued to improve his times, and set a new world record for the 200m at an IPC Grand Prix in Nottwil, Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishathletics.org.uk/media/news/2015-news-page/june-2015/01-06-15-nottwil/|title=Rowlings the Record Breaker|work=britishathletics.org.uk|date=1 June 2015|accessdate=2 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611120941/http://www.britishathletics.org.uk/media/news/2015-news-page/june-2015/01-06-15-nottwil/|archivedate=11 June 2015|df=}}</ref> Later that year he represented Kuwait at his [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|third World Championship]], this time in [[Doha]], Qatar. This time enough T33 athletes were available for Almutairi to race in his actual classification in a single race, the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m]]. In the final he set a championship record of 17.53 to beat his nearest rival, Britain's [[Dan Bramall]], by over a second and a half.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/eng/at/ATR173A_QA2015ATM133101ENG.htm|title=Results - Men's 100m T33 Final |accessdate=2 August 2016|date=28 October 2015|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]}}</ref> Almutairi also competed in the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 800 metres|800m T34]], but he finished a distant 8th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/eng/at/ATR173A_QA2015ATM830101ENG.htm|title=Results - Men's 800m T34 Final |accessdate=2 August 2016|date=26 October 2015|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=ahmad-almutairi|old_id=903822}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almutairi, Ahmad}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Kuwait]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti wheelchair racers]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti male javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti men's wheelchair basketball players]]\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes with cerebral palsy]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Male wheelchair racers]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Kuwait]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Kuwaiti para-sport athlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    =\n| name           = Ahmad Almutairi\n| image          = \n| image_size     = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels.-->\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     =\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = Kuwaiti \n| residence      = Kuwait City\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|05|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| weight         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| website        =\n| country        = Great Britain\n| sport          = [[Track and field]]<br/>[[Wheelchair basketball]]\n|disability_class= [[T33 (classification)|T33]] (athletics)\n| event          = sprint, javelin\n| club           = Kuwait Para-Sports Club\n| team           =\n| turnedpro      =\n| coach          = Mohamed Farhan\n| worlds         =\n| regionals      =\n| nationals      =\n| olympics       =\n| paralympics    = [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]\n| highestranking =\n| pb             =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport |Athletics}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{KUW}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Summer Paralympics]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 Paralympic Games|2016 Rio]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres T33|100m \u2013 T33]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m \u2013 T33]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T33]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Asian Para Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 Asian Para Games|2014 Incheon]] | 100m - T34}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 Asian Para Games|2014 Incheon]] | 200m - T34}}\n| show-medals    =\n| updated        =\n}}\n\n'''Ahmad Almutairi''' (born 13 May 1994) is a [[Kuwait]]i para-sport athlete who competes as a [[T33 (classification)|T33 classification]] [[track and field]] athlete and as a [[wheelchair basketball]] player, both at national level.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=903822&refreshauto=1|title=Almutairi, Ahmed|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> Despite the fact that Almutairi held the Paralympic world record for his classification in the 100m, 200m, 400m and 800m events, major world